TITLE: Credit Suisse to Borrow as Much as $54 Billion From Swiss Central Bank
SUMMARY: The Swiss lender had ended Wednesday fighting for its life, with shares at a record low and the cost to insure against a default the highest ever. The loan is an effort to avert further damage.

TITLE: No, Diversity Did Not Cause Silicon Valley Bank’s Collapse
SUMMARY: Blaming workplace diversity or environmentally and socially conscious investments for the firm’s downfall signals a “complete lack of understanding of how banks work,” one expert said.

TITLE: After SVB Collapse, Fed and Lawmakers Eye Bank Rules
SUMMARY: The stunning demise of Silicon Valley Bank has spurred soul-searching about how large and regional banks are overseen.

TITLE: French Protesters Rally in Last Angry Push Before Pension Bill Vote
SUMMARY: Many believe the legislation to raise the retirement age to 64 from 62 will pass Parliament, and they are looking beyond the vote to fight on.

TITLE: How Washington Decided to Rescue Silicon Valley Bank’s Depositors
SUMMARY: Officials were initially unsure about the need for the measures they eventually announced to shore up the financial system, but changed their minds quickly.

TITLE: Meta, Facebook’s Parent, to Lay Off Another 10,000 Workers
SUMMARY: It would be the tech company’s second round of cuts since November. Mark Zuckerberg, its chief executive, has declared 2023 the “year of efficiency.”

TITLE: Don’t Call It a Bailout: Washington Is Haunted by the 2008 Financial Crisis
SUMMARY: The colossal bailouts after the 2008 collapse arguably saved the global economy, but they also provoked a ferocious popular backlash.

TITLE: Was This a Bailout? Skeptics Descend on Silicon Valley Bank Response.
SUMMARY: The government took drastic action to shore up the banking system and make depositors of two failed banks whole. It quickly drew blowback.

TITLE: SVB Collapse Upsets Expectations for Federal Reserve’s Rate Decision
SUMMARY: The Fed has been rapidly raising interest rates to fight inflation. But making big moves could be trickier amid instability.

TITLE: Colleges Have Been a Small-Town Lifeline. What Happens as They Shrink?
SUMMARY: Declining student enrollment is hitting the rural areas that rely on universities. They’re trying to adapt to survive.

TITLE: Biden Rejects Spending Cuts and Embraces Tax Increases on Wealthy
SUMMARY: The president has met Republican demands for debt reduction with a plan to trim deficits by taxing companies and the rich.

TITLE: Can the United Farm Workers of California Rise Again?
SUMMARY: Decades after Cesar Chavez made the union a power in California fields, it has lost much of its clout. Membership dropped precipitously, from 60,000 to 5,500. It hopes a new law will turn the tide.

TITLE: Silicon Valley Bank’s Collapse Causes Strain for Young Companies
SUMMARY: Young companies raced to get their money out of the bank, which was central to the start-up industry. Some said they could not make payroll.

TITLE: Jobs Report Gives Fed a Mixed Signal Ahead of Its March Decision
SUMMARY: The Federal Reserve is anxiously parsing incoming data as it decides between a small or a large rate move this month.

TITLE: U.S. Employers Keep Hiring, but Signs of Easing Are Seen
SUMMARY: The economy added 311,000 jobs in February despite higher interest rates. But hourly earnings rose more slowly as the pool of available workers grew.

TITLE: Why Russia Has Such a Strong Grip on Europe’s Nuclear Power
SUMMARY: New energy sources to replace oil and natural gas have been easier to find than kicking the dependency on Rosatom, the state-owned nuclear superstore.

TITLE: Rebecca Blank, Who Changed How Poverty Is Measured, Dies at 67
SUMMARY: As an economics professor, she found serious flaws in how government determines who is poor in America. As under secretary of commerce, she fixed them.

TITLE: Biden’s $6.8 Trillion Budget Proposes New Social Programs and Higher Taxes
SUMMARY: The president requested trillions in new spending that has no chance of passing a Republican House, even as he sought to reduce deficits by raising taxes on businesses and the rich.

TITLE: Why Poverty Persists in America
SUMMARY: A Pulitzer Prize-winning sociologist offers a new explanation for an intractable problem.

TITLE: U.S. and Europe Angle for New Deal to Resolve Climate Spat
SUMMARY: American and European officials are trying to reach agreement on the outlines of a limited trade deal that could help resolve a major rift over America’s new climate legislation.
